\begin_inset Formula $|f^{2}(x)-f^{2}(x_{0})|=|f^{2}(x)-z|<\frac{z}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of width at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 within 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{2}(x)>\frac{z}{2}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,f\rangle=\int_{0}^{L}f^{2}(x)\,dx\geq\int_{I}f^{2}(x)\,dx\geq\delta\frac{z}{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\neq\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,f\rangle\neq0$
\end_inset

, or contrapositively if 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,f\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
